history.content:
We don't yet know whether or not we'll be able to enroll everybody in CS 189/289A who wants to take it in Spring 2022. For the sake of transparency, here's what to expect.

There are two offerings of CS 189 in Spring 2022. Lecture 2, taught by Marvin Zhang, is for undergraduate Data Science majors only. Conversely, if you are an undergraduate Data Science major, please enroll in Lecture 2, not Lecture 1. Lecture 1, taught by me, is for everybody else.

If you are a graduate student, please enroll in CS 289A, not 189. (That's Lecture 1 only.) If you are an undergraduate, please enroll in CS 189, not 289A. (Sorry, but we don't have enough staff to offer Projects to the undergrads.) We will enforce this strictly. If you've already enrolled in the wrong one, I think Cindy Conners can move you to the right one.

I will prioritize students (in Lecture 1) as follows:

  • EECS grad students have the highest priority. This includes EECS M.Eng. students. All of them will be enrolled.
  • Undergraduates are second. They will be prioritized in the usual manner of the university's registration system. Only in very unusual cases am I willing to interfere with the standard campus waitlist ordering. (I think things like Phase I vs. Phase II, seniors vs. juniors vs. sophomores, etc. should work as advertised.)
  • Non-EECS grad students are third. Sorry, but I think it's right for the EECS Department to serve our own grad students and our undergrad population first. You're smart enough to learn this material yourself if you need to.
  • Concurrent enrollment students are last. However, I may make exceptions for exchange students who have traveled to spend a semester or two at Berkeley. Make sure your application explains your circumstances well. Don't expect to be admitted before week 4 of classes.
  • There are 9 seats set aside for GLOBE students, separate from the prioritization scheme above.
  • "Auditors" are welcome (if you have a CalNet account), but please do not submit homeworks or exams.  Our capacity is primarily limited by our staff for grading. The university does not have an official auditor status, but you can come to lectures and discussion sections and join the class Piazza.

It's too soon to know whether everybody who wants to get into the course will get in or not. Last time I taught the class, in Spring 2021, everybody who persisted to the last possible minute got into the class (by the middle of week 4), but just barely. Typically, 100+ students drop during the first four weeks of the class. Homework 2 will be a difficult math homework designed to help you figure out whether you have mastered the prerequisites (linear algebra, probability, multivariable calculus) well enough to survive this class. For that reason, a fair number of students typically drop the class by the time Homework 2 is due.

If you are still waitlisted when the lectures begin, please attend classes, submit homeworks, stay on the waitlist, and have hope (though there are no guarantees). We will give you access to Piazza and Gradescope without being formally admitted. Please keep up; there have been occasions when a student gets a surprise admission in week 4 but hasn't done the homework. Don't be that student!

Lastly, please do not read too much into the "capacity"/"open seats" numbers on classes.berkeley.edu. There are two separate classes, CS 189 and CS 289A, constituting Lecture 1, but classes.berkeley.edu is not smart enough to know that they're both sharing the same capacity. Seats have to be manually shifted back and forth between the classes as needed. So those numbers are not reliable in any way.

Thank you,

Jonathan Shewchuk

UPDATE:

The Piazza for CS 189/289A, Lecture 1, is live and you can self-enroll at piazza.com/berkeley/spring2022/cs189289a . Once there, please follow the instructions there for self-enrolling in Gradescope as well. Again, students who hope to be enrolled in the class should be submitting homeworks, even if you are not yet enrolled. If you are enrolling in Lecture 2 (for Data Science majors), this is not your Piazza nor your Gradescope.
